The underlying principle that explains their performance advantage is the relationship between high activations and high parameter gradients.

This projection captures the most informative aspects of the model's learned representations, which are crucial for distinguishing between in-distribution and out-of-distribution data. By concentrating on these high-gradient activations, ASH and similar methods can more effectively identify OOD samples, as they are more likely to trigger significant changes in the model's parameters. This approach leverages the inherent structure of the model's learned representations, making it a powerful technique for OOD detection.
